The position of Bacon mid-way, as it were, between Scholasticism‚ on one side, and Modern Philosophy and Science, on the other, is so interesting that l cannot but think that much has even still to be learnt from the study of his works, and especially os this, the chief and most influential ol them all. Not only is the Novum Organum a collection ol fine sayings and suggestive remarks, but a knowledge ol it is indispensable to the student os the History either ol Logic, of Philosophy, or ol the Physical Sciences. Moreover, it lurnishes an excellent starting-point in the history os anylof these subjects, whether we wish to go backwards or sorwards.
